body:
@zyfrank It would mean anyone could pay the gas for the approval transaction. For example, an exchange might pay the gas for the the approval transaction because they would make money on the subsequent sale of the token.

@pvienhage Thanks for expressing interest in this issue. Two questions:

1. Do you have any public smart contract code or smart contract auditing experience that I can verify and review? I'd like to check references for this bounty.

2. Are you able to confirm that meta transactions for approvals and transfers in an ERC721 contract will achieve what I am looking for? That is, will these new functions give a new account with 1 token and 0 eth the ability to sell that token on a 0x decentralized exchange? I understand if you can't confirm, but I'm curious to know if my understanding is correct.

@pvienhage Ok thanks. That sounds good.

Can you clarify where the nonce is coming from? I had not previously considered the possibility of replay attacks with meta transactions, but I can now see the risk.

Is the nonce you're describing different than the one used in normal transactions?
